{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"0aa43490-44e0-11ed-8769-ad7721992925","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-one","ref":"7631c3a5-75dd-450b-a8cc-54385c65e0ae","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"17.7 Advice for the Financial Manager","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"445df8c4-fb71-4641-805e-01ff181a1933"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"25d73606-4475-4f65-a66f-afe34c0129c7","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Payout policy decisions are related to the capital structure decisions we discussed in ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"ec98559a-37fc-4b38-96cb-1d3541de4fcb","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Chapter 16","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"637adc80-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":". The amount of debt the firm has determines how much cash flow is precommitted to debt holders as interest payments and how much will be left for possible distribution to shareholders or reinvestment in the firm. Furthermore, distributing capital to shareholders reduces the equity left in the firm, increasing leverage. When setting the amount of the payout to shareholders, the financial manager needs to carefully weigh the future investment plans of the firm. If the manager expects to make large investment expenditures in the near future, then it does not make sense to make a large distribution to shareholders only to quickly return to the markets for new capital financing (either through debt or additional equity as discussed in ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"393eda67-89c2-4ada-857a-847d7505e629","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Chapters 14","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"4dc15680-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":" and ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"fb26380c-7ff9-4759-81c3-a0a9e93e4b02","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"15","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"52d11d40-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":"). Overall, as a financial manager you should consider the following when making payout policy decisions:","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"ed711d79-0e3a-4775-a528-cf29ff81a144"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"1","startValue":1},"ref":"000dc2a9-0f1c-403c-8b99-701701590ba4","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"83cd715a-4158-46d7-8de5-e9768b5ca9cb","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"f3c4dec5-e9a1-4b2d-8c9a-ec3df642d569","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"For a given payout amount, try to maximize the after-tax payout to the shareholders. Repurchases and dividends are often taxed differently and one can have an advantage over the other.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"29facf14-778e-42bb-91e3-f74c86972580","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"ed5cb8b9-4eec-46ef-abf6-090eb468ab02","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Repurchases and special dividends are useful for making large, infrequent distributions to shareholders. Neither implies any expectation of repeated payouts.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"24caa831-9e44-44c4-aa18-f3f232cd17d7","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"17a999f7-c546-43bc-9845-214fb7035944","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Starting and increasing a regular dividend is seen by shareholders as an implicit commitment to maintain this level of regular payout indefinitely. Only set regular dividend levels that you are confident the firm can maintain.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"11909ed3-f8b9-414e-acc4-05e7c8c9d67a","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"f6afbcfa-464d-40eb-b7a4-b7daf80f247b","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Because regular dividends are seen as an implicit commitment, they send a stronger signal of financial strength to shareholders than do infrequent distributions such as repurchases. However, this signal comes with a cost because regular payouts reduce a firmâ€™s financial flexibility.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"e8cabf79-e98f-4fa0-853f-4eed820845fd","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"0f2bdfd9-7d11-46c6-b24e-39936724baeb","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Be mindful of future investment plans. There are transaction costs associated with both distributions and raising new capital, so it is expensive to make a large distribution and then raise capital to fund a project. It would be better to make a smaller distribution and fund the project internally.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"2f2a1ecc-fdc8-422f-ac70-a8c7eee70298"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"6e1988b4-2652-40dc-89ac-95dad3c530d7","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"6fb72726-1476-4155-8a3d-0b55ef82f7d6","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Table 17.6","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"8b0dc820-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":" briefly summarizes these considerations as a series of questions you should ask yourself when deciding whether to make a distribution and what form it should take.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"371af6cd-b078-4d86-a8ab-f2c34bf9f68a"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-table","config":{"activityLabel":"Table 17.6","instructions":"","tableCaptionText":"","activityTitle":"Navigating the Payout Decision","tableTitle":"","captions":"","credit":""},"value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"id":"ch17table06"},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Payout or Not","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"db971be4-020f-491d-9128-fc256cc980eb"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Dividend or Repurchase","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"302b127a-3b6e-4bd8-96f3-27b81e57a0af"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"e6b774fd-0b95-45ac-9288-36b6dd0504e8"}],"object":"block","type":"table-head","ref":"455ebbc5-b43b-4b69-9f59-e65a72f52a6b"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Do we have any unfunded positive-NPV projects?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"ca195939-ac8a-4e5c-a0e7-c2ebdc4dfffb"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"What are the tax implications for our shareholder base?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"5b356864-b144-4124-baba-3b2f7d589f14"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"d5f73ac7-ca3d-4283-b66c-e7daa902145d"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"What are our future investment plans?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"074950ab-0ddc-49ff-bb4c-992f53087356"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Do we value the flexibility that repurchases allow?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"5412b9c8-57d8-44e0-9f89-02db4a4c9823"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"9c63b380-5180-42bc-bcc9-63e77662194f"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Do we have sufficient cash reserves to weather a recession without distress?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"1b693acd-ecd3-4557-b70c-f87bd4821a6b"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Do we need to send the stronger signal that dividends would convey?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"408908b8-f1ea-4208-b023-f52f1c818d0f"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"c9fdf60e-ab57-4bc7-8368-04f5e9f7fafd"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Would we benefit from signaling financial strength to the market?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"3c75a5b3-677a-4431-8bba-d7e4abcd3bfb"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"d8ffeee3-795b-45a5-a986-7f0b564e546e"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"b7b8728c-e33d-4065-886b-b9cbd3947f05"}],"object":"block","type":"table-body","ref":"6ebc5549-c81c-47d3-9e7c-dfd89956c7cb"}],"object":"block","type":"table","ref":"7a9221f7-526f-4fe4-8d7b-9a0c6fa0ce49"}]}},"ref":"2ed7af53-4d42-45eb-902f-8781672d2e92"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-table","config":{"activityLabel":"","instructions":"","tableCaptionText":"","activityTitle":"","tableTitle":"","captions":"","credit":""},"value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"id":"ch17intbl05"},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"KEY POINTS AND EQUATIONS","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"26d835e6-a88f-4786-b071-b8d92b4d4b24"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"KEY TERMS","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"06d94d31-0319-4d58-b366-1f73bf865dc0"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"6120fff4-f723-44d5-90ab-cec99962b343"}],"object":"block","type":"table-head","ref":"bb02908d-a6d1-4fba-81b6-2b6921ccaaf6"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"17.1 Cash Distributions to Shareholders","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"data":{"reference":"76cead20-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"},"ref":"4ff5c0c0-3dc7-4971-89fd-b3818840a86c"}],"data":{}},{"object":"block","type":"unordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"","startValue":""},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"When a firm wants to distribute cash to its shareholders, it can pay a cash dividend or it can repurchase shares.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"ref":"bed7eda5-c422-4315-a6ba-a88347b6b692"},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Most companies pay regular, quarterly dividends. Sometimes firms announce one-time, special dividends.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"ref":"03a4b1c5-8bfc-4ed1-93ed-ce4baa48ac96"},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Firms repurchase shares using an open market repurchase, a tender offer, a Dutch auction repurchase, or a targeted repurchase.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"ref":"b6f81cee-3205-401b-a642-34bf97905276"},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"On the declaration date, firms announce that they will pay dividends to all shareholders of record on the record date. The ex-dividend date is the first day on which the stock trades without the right to an upcoming dividend; it is usually two trading days prior to the record date. Dividends are paid on the payment date.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"ref":"c95c777e-1033-458f-941f-be08d1c392f3"}],"ref":"d85c0666-2137-4678-b3af-b92dea0628b5"}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"6f7cfc5e-04cc-4e01-81e3-ac2bb8232682"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"unordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"","startValue":""},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"declaration date","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"data":{"reference":"7b2758e0-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"},"ref":"95dc8b76-6b2d-44cf-9322-3a6255476516"}],"data":{}}],"ref":"4a9d9d14-eeb3-480a-a3d9-b1bd67dff56f"},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","nodes":